To be direct: You cannot play APK files natively on a Wii U.

APK files are designed for the Android operating system, while the Wii U uses a proprietary PowerPC-based OS. Because the Wii U’s hardware architecture is fundamentally different from a modern smartphone or tablet, there is no Android emulator or "compatibility layer" that allows Android apps to run on the console.

If you are looking to expand what your Wii U can do, here are your best alternatives:

1. Wii U Homebrew (The "Real" Way to Mod)
While you can't run APKs, you can run homebrew apps specifically made for the Wii U. These provide many of the features people usually want from Android apps:

Emulators: Play NES, SNES, Genesis, GameCube, and even some N64 games via RetroArch or standalone apps.

Media Players: Apps like Wii U Media Player can stream videos from your network.

Custom Games: There are many fan-made ports of PC and arcade games.

How to do it: You typically need an SD card and a specific environment like Aroma or Tiramisu. You can find the definitive guide at wiiu.hacks.guide.

2. Play Wii U Games on Android
If your goal was actually the reverse—playing Wii U games on your phone—that is possible.

Cemu for Android: The famous PC emulator Cemu recently released an official Android version.

Requirements: You will need a high-end Android device (Snapdragon 8 Gen 1 or better is recommended) and your own legally dumped game files.

3. Why it won't work
Architecture: Android apps are built for ARM or x86 processors. The Wii U uses a PowerPC processor. They don't speak the same "language."

RAM: The Wii U only has 2GB of RAM (with only 1GB available for games), which is significantly less than what modern Android apps require to function.

