Here is your roadmap to go from nothing to your first running code.

1. Install the Toolchain (The Compiler)
You cannot use standard Windows or Mac compilers (like Visual Studio) alone because they don't know how to talk to a Wii U's PowerPC processor.

Download devkitPro: Go to devkitpro.org and download the installer for your OS.

Select "Wii U": During installation, it will ask which consoles you want to develop for. Check the box for Wii U (wiiu-dev).

Check your environment: After installing, open a terminal (or Command Prompt) and type: powerpc-eabi-gcc --version If it returns a version number, you are ready to compile.

2. Understand the File Formats
You aren't making .apk or .exe files. You are making:

.rpx: The raw executable (similar to an .elf file).

.wuhb: The modern "Wii U Homebrew Bundle." This is what you want. It contains your icon, your meta-data, and your code, and it runs directly from the Aroma homebrew environment.

3. Your First "Hello World"
Wii U programming uses C or C++. Below is a very stripped-down example of what a main file (main.c) looks like using the WUT library. This prints text to the screen.

C++
#include <wut.h>
#include <stdio.h>

int main(int argc, char **argv) {
    // Initialize the screen (OSScreen)
    OSScreenInit();

    // Get the buffer sizes for the TV and Gamepad
    uint32_t tv_size = OSScreenGetBufferSizeEx(SCREEN_TV);
    
    // Set up the memory for the screens (simplified)
    OSScreenSetBufferEx(SCREEN_TV, (void*)0xF4000000);
    OSScreenEnableEx(SCREEN_TV, 1);

    while(1) {
        // Clear the screen
        OSScreenClearBufferEx(SCREEN_TV, 0x00000000);

        // Print text (x, y, text)
        OSScreenPutFontEx(SCREEN_TV, 0, 0, "Hello Wii U! This is my first app.");

        // Flip the buffers to show the drawing
        OSScreenFlipBuffersEx(SCREEN_TV);
        
        // Brief logic to exit if the 'Home' button is pressed
        // (Requires KPAD/VPAD input libraries)
    }

    return 0;
}
