Since you are ready to roll, let’s get your project structure set up. Unlike Android development (where Android Studio handles the folders), Wii U development relies on a Makefile system.

Here is how you should organize your first project folder so the compiler knows where to find everything:

1. Create Your Project Folder
Create a folder named MyWiiUApp. Inside it, create the following structure:

MyWiiUApp/

src/ (Put your .c or .cpp files here)

include/ (Put your .h header files here)

resources/ (Put your icon.png and images here)

Makefile (The "instruction manual" for the compiler)

2. The Makefile (The Most Important Part)
The Makefile tells devkitPro how to turn your code into a Wii U app. Instead of writing one from scratch, you should copy a template.

Navigate to your devkitPro installation (usually C:\devkitPro\wut\share\wut.mk or similar).

The easiest way to start is to copy the Makefile from the WUT Hello World sample.

Place that Makefile in your MyWiiUApp/ root folder.

3. Writing the Code
Open a text editor (VS Code is great for this) and create a file called main.c inside your src/ folder. Use this template—it’s a bit more "complete" than the previous one as it includes the Main Loop that allows you to exit back to the menu:

C
#include <coreinit/screen.h>
#include <coreinit/thread.h>
#include <vpad/input.h>
#include <stdio.h>

int main(int argc, char **argv) {
    // 1. Initialize the Screen
    OSScreenInit();
    
    // 2. Set up buffers for TV and Gamepad
    uint32_t tv_size = OSScreenGetBufferSizeEx(SCREEN_TV);
    uint32_t drc_size = OSScreenGetBufferSizeEx(SCREEN_DRC);
    
    // This is a simplified memory setup for beginners
    OSScreenSetBufferEx(SCREEN_TV, (void*)0xF4000000);
    OSScreenSetBufferEx(SCREEN_DRC, (void*)(0xF4000000 + tv_size));
    
    OSScreenEnableEx(SCREEN_TV, 1);
    OSScreenEnableEx(SCREEN_DRC, 1);

    VPADStatus vpad_status;
    VPADReadError error;

    // 3. The Main Loop
    while (1) {
        // Read Gamepad input
        VPADRead(VPAD_CHAN_0, &vpad_status, 1, &error);

        // Exit if 'Home' button is pressed
        if (vpad_status.hold & VPAD_BUTTON_HOME) {
            break;
        }

        // Clear screens (Grey background)
        OSScreenClearBufferEx(SCREEN_TV, 0x4B4B4B00);
        OSScreenClearBufferEx(SCREEN_DRC, 0x4B4B4B00);

        // Print text
        OSScreenPutFontEx(SCREEN_TV, 0, 0, "Hello World on the TV!");
        OSScreenPutFontEx(SCREEN_DRC, 0, 0, "Hello World on the Gamepad!");

        // Flip buffers to render
        OSScreenFlipBuffersEx(SCREEN_TV);
        OSScreenFlipBuffersEx(SCREEN_DRC);
    }

    return 0;
}
4. Compiling
Open your Terminal / Command Prompt.

Navigate to your MyWiiUApp folder.

Type make.

If successful, you will see a new file: MyWiiUApp.rpx.

5. Moving to the Console
If you are using Aroma (the current standard for Wii U homebrew):

Take your SD Card.

Put the .rpx file in: SD:/wiiu/apps/MyWiiUApp/MyWiiUApp.rpx.

Put the SD card in your Wii U and launch it from the home menu.

