To take your app to the next level, let’s handle touch input and prepare for graphics.

1. Handling Touch Input
The Wii U Gamepad uses a resistive touchscreen, meaning it tracks one point at a time. In the WUT library, this data is stored in the VPADStatus struct.

Modify your main loop to detect where the user is touching:

C++
#include <vpad/input.h>
#include <stdio.h>

// Inside your while(1) loop:
VPADStatus vpad_status;
VPADReadError error;
VPADRead(VPAD_CHAN_0, &vpad_status, 1, &error);

if (vpad_status.tpNormal.touched) {
    // The screen is being touched!
    // X and Y coordinates are usually 0-3900 (internal scale)
    // We can scale them to the screen resolution (854x480)
    int touchX = vpad_status.tpNormal.x;
    int touchY = vpad_status.tpNormal.y;

    // Print the coordinates to the Gamepad screen for debugging
    char buffer[50];
    sprintf(buffer, "Touch: X %d, Y %d", touchX, touchY);
    OSScreenPutFontEx(SCREEN_DRC, 0, 5, buffer);
}
2. Displaying Images (The Next Frontier)
Printing text with OSScreen is easy, but it’s very slow and only supports basic text. To display images (like your icon.png or a character), you have two main paths:

Option A: Software Rendering (Beginner)
You can manually write pixel data to the framebuffer.

Pros: Easy to understand.

Cons: Very slow; cannot do 60fps games.

Option B: GX2 (Professional/Advanced)
The Wii U uses a GPU API called GX2. This is how you get 60fps, HD graphics, and 3D.

Pros: Hardware accelerated, used by all commercial games.

Cons: Extremely complex. You have to manage shaders, vertex buffers, and textures.

3. Your "Real" Next Step: Use a Library
Most Wii U developers don't write "naked" GX2 code because it's too hard. Instead, they use a wrapper library.

I highly recommend looking into SDL2 for Wii U.

If you learn SDL2, you can use standard functions like SDL_RenderCopy() to draw images.

It handles the Wii U's touch input and Gamepad buttons automatically.

Bonus: Code you write in SDL2 can be easily ported to PC or other consoles.

