This is where things get exciting. SDL2 (Simple DirectMedia Layer) is the industry standard for 2D games. It replaces the slow OSScreen text with actual hardware-accelerated graphics.

1. Install SDL2 for Wii U
Before compiling this, you must install the library via your terminal: dkp-pacman -S wiiu-sdl2 wiiu-sdl2_image

2. The SDL2 Template
This code initializes both the TV and Gamepad, sets up a "Renderer" (the engine), and draws a colored rectangle that follows your finger on the Gamepad.

C++
#include <SDL2/SDL.h>
#include <stdbool.h>

int main(int argc, char* argv[]) {
    // 1. Initialize SDL2 Video
    SDL_Init(SDL_INIT_VIDEO);

    // 2. Create a Window (Wii U treats this as both TV and Gamepad)
    SDL_Window* window = SDL_CreateWindow("My Wii U Game", 
                                          SDL_WINDOWPOS_UNDEFINED, SDL_WINDOWPOS_UNDEFINED, 
                                          1280, 720, 0);

    // 3. Create a Renderer (The "Brush" we use to draw)
    SDL_Renderer* renderer = SDL_CreateRenderer(window, -1, SDL_RENDERER_ACCELERATED);

    bool running = true;
    SDL_Event event;
    SDL_Rect playerRect = { 615, 335, 50, 50 }; // X, Y, Width, Height

    // 4. Main Loop
    while (running) {
        // Handle Events (Input)
        while (SDL_PollEvent(&event)) {
            if (event.type == SDL_QUIT) running = false;
            
            // Touch Input
            if (event.type == SDL_FINGERDOWN || event.type == SDL_FINGERMOTION) {
                playerRect.x = event.tfinger.x * 1280 - 25;
                playerRect.y = event.tfinger.y * 720 - 25;
            }
        }

        // --- DRAWING ---
        // Set background color to Dark Blue
        SDL_SetRenderDrawColor(renderer, 20, 20, 100, 255);
        SDL_RenderClear(renderer);

        // Set draw color to Red for our square
        SDL_SetRenderDrawColor(renderer, 255, 0, 0, 255);
        SDL_RenderFillRect(renderer, &playerRect);

        // Present to the screen
        SDL_RenderPresent(renderer);
    }

    // Cleanup
    SDL_DestroyRenderer(renderer);
    SDL_DestroyWindow(window);
    SDL_Quit();
    return 0;
}
3. Update your Makefile
Since you are now using SDL2, your Makefile needs to know to "link" those libraries. Look for the LIBS line in your Makefile and update it:

Makefile
# Add these to your existing LIBS line
LIBS    := -lSDL2_image -lSDL2 -lpng -ljpeg -lz -lm -lwut
4. Why this is better
Performance: OSScreen was like drawing with a typewriter. SDL2 is like drawing with a modern GPU.

Touch: Notice event.tfinger.x. SDL2 normalizes touch coordinates from 0.0 to 1.0, so you don't have to worry about the weird 0–3900 Wii U internal scale.

Gamepad Mirroring: By default, SDL2 on Wii U will show the exact same thing on the TV and the Gamepad.

5. Next Level: Adding Images
To show a character instead of a red box, you would:

Put player.png in your content folder.

Load it as a "Texture" using IMG_LoadTexture(renderer, "wfs:/player.png");.

Draw it using SDL_RenderCopy().

