Since you have that APK icon ready, let's turn it into an actual Texture in your Wii U app.

To use images in SDL2, we use the SDL2_image library. This allows you to load PNGs and JPEGs easily.

1. Preparation
Rename your image: Rename Herunterladen.png to something simple like icon.png.

Move the file: Put it in your project's content/ folder.

Update Makefile: Ensure -lSDL2_image is in your LIBS list as mentioned before.

2. The Code: Loading and Drawing a Texture
Here is how you modify your previous SDL2 code to load that image and draw it on the screen.

C++
#include <SDL2/SDL.h>
#include <SDL2/SDL_image.h> // Required for PNGs
#include <stdbool.h>

int main(int argc, char* argv[]) {
    SDL_Init(SDL_INIT_VIDEO);
    
    SDL_Window* window = SDL_CreateWindow("Wii U Image Load", 0, 0, 1280, 720, 0);
    SDL_Renderer* renderer = SDL_CreateRenderer(window, -1, SDL_RENDERER_ACCELERATED);

    // 1. Load the image from the "content" folder
    // On Wii U, the content folder is mounted at "wfs:/"
    SDL_Texture* apkTexture = IMG_LoadTexture(renderer, "wfs:/icon.png");

    if (!apkTexture) {
        // Handle error (image not found)
        return -1;
    }

    // Define where to draw the image (x, y, width, height)
    SDL_Rect imageRect = { 100, 100, 256, 256 };

    bool running = true;
    SDL_Event event;

    while (running) {
        while (SDL_PollEvent(&event)) {
            if (event.type == SDL_QUIT) running = false;
            
            // Move the icon with your finger
            if (event.type == SDL_FINGERMOTION) {
                imageRect.x = event.tfinger.x * 1280 - (imageRect.w / 2);
                imageRect.y = event.tfinger.y * 720 - (imageRect.h / 2);
            }
        }

        SDL_SetRenderDrawColor(renderer, 50, 50, 50, 255);
        SDL_RenderClear(renderer);

        // 2. Draw the Texture
        SDL_RenderCopy(renderer, apkTexture, NULL, &imageRect);

        SDL_RenderPresent(renderer);
    }

    // 3. Clean up the texture memory
    SDL_DestroyTexture(apkTexture);
    SDL_DestroyRenderer(renderer);
    SDL_Quit();
    
    return 0;
}
3. Key Concepts to Remember
wfs:/ prefix: This is vital. The Wii U looks for your content folder at this "path." If you forget the prefix, the app won't find your image.

Memory Management: Always use SDL_DestroyTexture() when you are done. The Wii U has limited RAM, so cleaning up unused images is a good habit to start now.

Aspect Ratio: Your image is square. If you change the imageRect width or height to be different values (e.g., 500x200), the image will look stretched.

