To add sound, we’ll use the SDL_mixer library. This is the standard way to handle music and sound effects in SDL2.

1. Install the Audio Library
Run this in your terminal to add the mixer support to your devkitPro setup: dkp-pacman -S wiiu-sdl2_mixer

2. The Code: Playing Background Music
This snippet shows how to initialize the audio system, load an audio file from your content folder, and play it on a loop.

C++
#include <SDL2/SDL.h>
#include <SDL2/SDL_mixer.h> // New library for audio

int main(int argc, char* argv[]) {
    SDL_Init(SDL_INIT_VIDEO | SDL_INIT_AUDIO); // Initialize Audio too

    // 1. Initialize SDL_mixer
    // Parameters: Frequency (44100), Format, Channels (2 for Stereo), Chunk size
    if (Mix_OpenAudio(44100, MIX_DEFAULT_FORMAT, 2, 2048) < 0) {
        return -1;
    }

    // 2. Load your music file from the content folder
    // Support for .mp3, .ogg, .wav, etc.
    Mix_Music *bgm = Mix_LoadMUS("wfs:/background_music.mp3");

    // 3. Play the music
    // -1 means loop forever
    Mix_PlayMusic(bgm, -1);

    // ... Your existing SDL_Renderer and Loop code goes here ...

    while (running) {
        // Your game logic
    }

    // 4. Cleanup
    Mix_FreeMusic(bgm);
    Mix_CloseAudio();
    // ... rest of your cleanup ...
}
3. Update your Makefile (Crucial)
You must link the mixer library. Update your LIBS line in the Makefile again:

Makefile
# Add -lSDL2_mixer to your list
LIBS    := -lSDL2_mixer -lSDL2_image -lSDL2 -lpng -ljpeg -lz -lm -lwut
4. Pro-Tip: Sound Effects vs. Music
In SDL_mixer, there is a difference between Music and Chunks:

Mix_Music: Use this for long background tracks (usually one at a time).

Mix_Chunk: Use this for short sound effects (explosions, clicks, jumps). You can play many of these at once.

Example: Mix_Chunk *sound = Mix_LoadWAV("wfs:/click.wav");

Play: Mix_PlayChannel(-1, sound, 0);

